The paper deals with the problem of network alignment, which is a common topic in several subfields of computer science. However, the use of spectral centrality measures and percolation techniques to solve the problem without prior information suggests that the paper is more likely to belong to the sub-categories of Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS), and Machine Learning (cs.LG). Additionally, the use of numerical experiments to evaluate the performance of the proposed algorithm suggests that the paper could also belong to the sub-categories of Systems and Control (cs.SY) and Networking and Internet Architecture (cs.NI).
